export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>The best-proven metal–organic framework (MOF) in industrial service removes about one tonne of CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> per day from cement flue gas; the best-known MOF in the scientific literature is thermodynamically doomed to hydrolyze in water. Between those two facts sits this chapter's class — MOFs, covalent organic frameworks, zeolites, and 2D materials (MXenes, transition-metal dichalcogenides, TMDCs) — whose cohesion is dominated by van der Waals (vdW) dispersion, binding on taxonomy modes 6 and 8 (§3.2). My claim is narrower than the usual one: the errors are real, quantified, and correctable in principle, but the binding constraint on value is not uptake, capacitance, or binding energy. It is predicting what survives water.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-1-1", "html": "<p>In 2023, Svante's CALF-20 filters removed about one tonne of CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> per day from flue gas at a Canadian cement plant, and BASF scaled production of the sorbent to several hundred tonnes per year.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"61\">[61]</sup> Its inventor, George Shimizu, describes CALF-20 as the first MOF &quot;proven stable and effective enough to be used at an industrial scale.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"330\">[330]</sup> That is the entire industrial base of MOF carbon capture as of 2026-07-17: one material, point-source service, not direct air capture (DAC).</p>\n<p>The US Department of Energy's Carbon Negative Shot commits to net CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> removal at gigaton scale for under $100 per tonne by 2032, backed by $1.27 billion across 21 carbon-removal pilots.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"64\">[64]</sup> China's 15th Five-Year Plan targets a 17% carbon-intensity cut for 2026–2030 after achieving about 12% against an 18% target in the 14th, naming carbon capture, utilization, and storage (CCUS) a key decarbonization technology.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"63\">[63]</sup> That gap — policy pull without a validated, water-stable, DAC-grade framework — is a simulation gap before it is a synthesis gap.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-2-1", "html": "<p>Start with the layered materials, where dispersion <em>is</em> the cohesive physics. Benchmarked against random-phase-approximation (RPA) interlayer energies for graphite, h-BN, and six MX<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> bilayers, semi-empirical vdW corrections deviate by factors of 0.77–3.04: DFT-D2 spans 0.81–1.73, DFT-MBD 0.77–1.82, and DFT-TS — the worst case — 1.36–3.04, a threefold overbinding.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"16\">[16]</sup> For MoS<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>, surface-energy estimates span 0.07–0.32 N/m across liquid-exfoliation inference, early vdW-DFT, and RPA — a better-than-fourfold spread on the quantity that sets exfoliation cost.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"85\">[85]</sup> A 2025 benchmark of 12 TMDCs across 11 vdW schemes — a ChemRxiv preprint, not yet peer-reviewed — finds no universally superior method: D3M variants overbind, the original vdW-DF and vdW-DF2 underbind, and only a four-scheme subset (PBE+D3, vdW-DF-CX and two cousins) is balanced.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"331\">[331]</sup></p>\n<p>This chapter's caution applies to itself. The spread does not mean dispersion is intractable: the balanced schemes reproduce RPA-consistent binding on well-characterized systems, and DFT-D3 matches experimental MoS<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> binding energies.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"332\">[332]</sup> It means there is no transferable default: each scheme is a local solution, and changing the chalcogenide or the property forces re-validation. Dispersion, in this class, is a solved problem that keeps not being solved — scheme by scheme, material by material. And I push back on my own field's rhetoric: &quot;vdW errors diverge by 100%&quot; is true as a worst-case band and false as a working description. The honest statement is that the worst mainstream scheme is 3<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> off, the best sit within ~20%, and you cannot know which one you are holding without an RPA or experimental anchor.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-2-2", "html": "<p>In porous frameworks the dispersion story turns erratic. With the same functional, the same adsorbate (CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>), and the same metal (Zn), PBE+D4 overbinds Zn-CHA by <span class=\"math\">$-9$</span> kJ/mol (<span class=\"math\">$-51$</span> vs <span class=\"math\">$-42$</span> experimental), underbinds Zn-MOF-74 by <span class=\"math\">$+11$</span> kJ/mol (<span class=\"math\">$-19$</span> vs <span class=\"math\">$-30$</span>; <span class=\"math\">$\\approx 0.11$</span> eV, with 96.485 kJ/mol = 1 eV), and lands within 2 kJ/mol for CALF-20 (<span class=\"math\">$-37$</span> vs <span class=\"math\">$-39$</span>).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"333\">[333]</sup> Sign-flipping <span class=\"math\">$\\pm 10$</span> kJ/mol errors on a 30–40 kJ/mol quantity are what a ranking-based screen cannot survive. MIL-53(Al)'s narrow-pore/large-pore energy difference — the quantity governing its guest-triggered breathing transition — spans 34–72 kJ/mol per unit cell across dispersion-corrected functionals, against an RPA+EC value of 7.4 kJ/mol: a 5–10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> overestimation, in a system where dispersion is required to stabilize the narrow-pore state at all.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"334\">[334]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"335\">[335]</sup> Even water binding in Mg-MOF-74, the most-studied capture MOF, needs coupled-cluster corrections on top of PBE+D3 to reproduce measured isotherms.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"336\">[336]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-2-3", "html": "<p>Machine-learned interatomic potentials (MLIPs) trained on one zeolite do not transfer to the next. Five architectures — MACE, NequIP, Allegro, MTP, Torch-ANI — trained on CHA with RPBE-D3 labels reach a best in-domain energy error of 0.05 meV/atom (MACE), then degrade by at least an order of magnitude on FAU, LTA, and MFI.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> MFI is hardest, mechanistically traced to unseen bond angles in its 10-membered rings versus CHA's 8-membered; MACE is least-bad, its force error growing only ~2<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> MS25's meta-lesson: low energy and force errors do not guarantee reliable observables.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> MOFSimBench — more than 20 universal MLIPs on MOF tasks — finds top universal models beating classical force fields and fine-tuned potentials, with training-data diversity, including out-of-equilibrium conformations, mattering more than architecture.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"337\">[337]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-2-4", "html": "<p>Water is this class's reality check, and it is thermodynamic, not merely kinetic. Calorimetry places the MOF-74 family's hydrolysis driving force 200–250 kJ/mol per metal center (<span class=\"math\">$\\approx 2.1$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$2.6$</span> eV) beyond that of ZIFs, and the authors' conclusion is blunt: these frameworks &quot;will eventually undergo hydrolysis,&quot; so room-temperature kinetic persistence masquerades as stability.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup> The commercial denominator matches the thermodynamics: more than 100,000 synthesized MOF structures have yielded a handful of products.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"338\">[338]</sup> The 2D side rhymes: Ti<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>C<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>T<span class=\"math\">$_x$</span> MXene dispersions degrade 42%, 85%, and 100% after 5, 10, and 15 days in an open vial, with water as the primary driver.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"111\">[111]</sup> I read this as the class-level evidence for the paper's stability thesis, which Chapter 14 develops in full.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 11.1 — Error ledger for porous frameworks and 2D materials (figures verified as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Quantity</th>\n<th>System</th>\n<th>Error or spread vs reference</th>\n<th>Source</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Interlayer vdW energy, ratio to RPA</td>\n<td>Graphite, h-BN, 6<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> MX<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> bilayers</td>\n<td>D2: 0.81–1.73; TS: 1.36–3.04; MBD: 0.77–1.82</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"16\">[16]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Specific surface energy</td>\n<td>MoS<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span></td>\n<td>0.07 (liquid exfoliation) to 0.32 N/m (RPA); &gt;4<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> spread</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"85\">[85]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> adsorption enthalpy</td>\n<td>Zn-MOF-74 (vs CALF-20, Zn-CHA)</td>\n<td>PBE+D4 <span class=\"math\">$-19$</span> vs <span class=\"math\">$-30$</span> kJ/mol exp. (<span class=\"math\">$+11 \\approx +0.11$</span> eV); CALF-20 <span class=\"math\">$-37$</span> vs <span class=\"math\">$-39$</span>; Zn-CHA <span class=\"math\">$-51$</span> vs <span class=\"math\">$-42$</span></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"333\">[333]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Narrow-pore/large-pore gap</td>\n<td>MIL-53(Al) breathing</td>\n<td>34–72 kJ/mol per cell (DFT-D3/vdW-DF) vs 7.4 kJ/mol (RPA+EC); 5–10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"334\">[334]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"335\">[335]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>MLIP energy error, cross-framework</td>\n<td>CHA<span class=\"math\">$\\rightarrow$</span>FAU/LTA/MFI zeolites</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$\\geq 10\\times$</span> degradation from 0.05 meV/atom in-domain; MFI hardest (unseen 10-ring bond angles); MACE force error only ~2<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span></td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Read the table as two layers of failure, with a third beyond it. The first four rows are label-layer: the reference method itself disagrees with higher-level theory by factors of roughly 1.2 to 10, so any MLIP trained on those labels inherits a scheme-dependent floor — this class's version of scoreboard row 10. Row five is model-layer: even with consistent labels, potentials fail at framework boundaries, where new ring topologies create unsampled local environments. Beyond the table sit the stability failures of §11.2.4, which are neither: accuracy on the pristine framework's energy surface says nothing about service life, because degradation is a different observable. The most dangerous row is the third. Systematic errors admit cheap linear corrections of the §3.4 lever-3 type; sign-flipping errors admit only fidelity escalation or per-material experimental anchoring.</p>\n<div class=\"pullbox\">\n<p><strong>Case box 11.1 — CALF-20 vs MOF-74: same field, opposite water fates.</strong> MOF-74 is the scientific champion: open metal sites, high uptake, thousands of citations. CALF-20 is the industrial champion: a zinc triazolate–oxalate framework that can be synthesized in water, survives wet acid flue gas with steam regeneration, and is the only MOF produced at scale by a major chemical company (BASF, several hundred tonnes per year) and the only one demonstrated on a cement plant (~1 t CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>/day, 2023).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"61\">[61]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"330\">[330]</sup> The simulation record mirrors the service record. For CALF-20, PBE+D4 predicts the CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> adsorption enthalpy within 2 kJ/mol of experiment; for MOF-74 the same functional misses by <span class=\"math\">$+11$</span> kJ/mol, and its water isotherms take coupled-cluster corrections to match.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"333\">[333]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"336\">[336]</sup> Meanwhile MOF-74's hydrolysis driving force exceeds that of ZIFs by 200–250 kJ/mol per metal — thermodynamically unstable in exactly the wet, temperature-cycled service where capture sorbents live.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup> A screen ranked on uptake picks MOF-74; a screen ranked on survival picks CALF-20. Same field, same adsorbate, opposite water fates — and standard DFT happens to be accurate for the one that survives. That coincidence is the parable of this class: the variable the field optimizes is not the variable that decides commercialization.</p>\n</div>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-3-1", "html": "<p>Two corrections apply, and neither requires inventing an architecture. The first is scoreboard row 4 (missing long-range physics): latent Ewald summation removes the unphysical interface and dipole artifacts of short-ranged MLIPs at roughly 2<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> cost — readiness M, demonstrated and waiting on default integration. The move is adoption, not reinvention. The data levers of §3.4 carry the rest: MOFSimBench's finding that training-set diversity beats architecture,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"337\">[337]</sup> plus MS25's transferability-first benchmarking,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> define the recipe — framework-diverse, out-of-equilibrium training data at one validated dispersion level, with cross-framework transfer reported as a first-class metric.</p>\n<p>The second correction is stability labels, and here I am blunt about the state of the art. ML water-stability classifiers exist but are triage tools. First-generation models reached 83% (two-class) and 71% (three-class) test accuracy.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"339\">[339]</sup> The WS24 effort enlarged training data by over 400% and reached ROC-AUC above 0.8.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"340\">[340]</sup> Independent re-benchmarking then found accuracy collapses under metal- and topology-grouped splits — an &quot;optimism gap&quot; — with some reported cross-dataset transfer turning out to be duplicate structures.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"341\">[341]</sup> Worse, the labels themselves are suspect: when room-temperature kinetic persistence is recorded as &quot;stable&quot; for frameworks carrying 200–250 kJ/mol hydrolysis driving forces, the classifier learns the wrong target.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup> The fix is not a better model but better labels — thermodynamic, calorimetry-anchored stability data, the §3.4 lever-3 philosophy applied to a new observable. That dataset is small, unglamorous, and within reach of a small lab.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-4", "html": "<p>The strongest skepticism comes from inside the field. Shimizu — inventor of the one industrial MOF — says plainly, &quot;there's a lot of hype versus reality.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"330\">[330]</sup> The DAC record supplies the second leg. One investigative report finds that Climeworks' Mammoth plant captured just over 100 t of CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> in 2024 against a 36,000 t/yr nameplate; Climeworks has not confirmed the figure and called it &quot;indicative of the ramp-up phase,&quot; and the earlier Orca plant has never surpassed ~1,000 t/yr against 4,000 t capacity.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"62\">[62]</sup> A 2024 expert elicitation put near-term DAC costs at $600–1,000/t, with even the most optimistic expert above $300/t today.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"342\">[342]</sup> I report these with restraint. Climeworks runs amine sorbents, not MOFs, and ramp-up failure is not sorbent failure. What the counter-narrative establishes is narrower and more useful: projections and policy targets are not evidence of feasibility.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-5", "html": "<p>Washington's instruments are real but turbulent. The DAC Hubs program committed $3.5 billion to four regional hubs of at least 1 MtCO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>/yr each, and the 45Q credit now pays $180/t for DAC with secure storage.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"343\">[343]</sup> The Carbon Negative Shot sets the &lt;$100/t-by-2032 target the field measures itself against.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"64\">[64]</sup> The caveat, as of 2026-07-17: the office that ran the hubs, OCED, was eliminated in the November 2025 DOE reorganization;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"60\">[60]</sup> the broader clean-energy hub cancellations were ruled illegal by a federal judge on January 12, 2026, with appeals pending;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"238\">[238]</sup> and the Energy Earthshots brand survives as dormant legacy content.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"239\">[239]</sup> Beijing's pull works differently: the 17% carbon-intensity cut, set after the previous plan's miss, plus CCUS's explicit naming, creates procurement pull for capture materials inside an efficiency mandate rather than a removal mandate.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"63\">[63]</sup> I treat both as demand signals for exactly what this class lacks — sorbents verified to survive service — and neither program's timeline as a forecast.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s11-6", "html": "<p>This chapter feeds the chain that reads: dispersion-corrected MLIPs <span class=\"math\">$\\rightarrow$</span> water-stable MOFs and COFs for DAC and low-energy separations <span class=\"math\">$\\rightarrow$</span> sub-$100/t carbon removal. Such funnels already close commercially: in the Kemira–CuspAI program, an industrial brief specifying water-stable, synthesizable chemistry up front ran a ~300-trillion-structure search down to 5,000 MOF designs and a priority candidate set in six months, under a framework agreement now scoping further classes.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup> Note what the brief specified first: water stability. My working bet follows directly. The money is not in predicting what maximizes uptake; it is in predicting what survives water. Uptake is a DFT calculation with a <span class=\"math\">$\\pm 10$</span> kJ/mol sign problem; survival is a label problem the field has barely started — and the lab that owns the thermodynamic stability dataset owns the axis everyone else is screening blind.</p>\n" },
]
